Gabriel N. Schaffer (gns2@po.CWRU.Edu) wrote:

: In a previous article, crobato@saba.kuentos.guam.net (Christopher Robato) says:

: >: Just to clear things up, NT is NOT a micro-kernel.  It is a bastard hybrid of
: >: a monolithic and micro-kernel design.  Microsoft simply states that it is
: >: because people like you seem to feel that "micro-kernel" means that it's
: >: better.  It does not.  It is simply a different solution.  Now then, _my_
: >: understanding is that IBM has been looking at the Mach kernel long before
: >: Microsoft designed and implemented the NT kernel.  In short, simply because
: >: IBM is using an off-shoot of the Mach kernel, doesn't mean they'll have a
: >: better kernel (although IBM's efforts appear to satisfy all the micro-kernel
: >: "requirements").  What does this really mean today?  Not a lot!  It could
: >: mean good things in days to come.  Mach is supposed to scale VERY well...much
: >: better than does NT today.  So, while SMP doesn't really mean much today,
: >: just imagine what a good SMP-capable OS can do in 5 years from now.
:    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
: Probably what NT does today.

: >Yes Greg, and I have to add something to that.  IBM's microkernel is a
: >very different animal than NT's to suggest that IBM is copying NT's
: >kernel.  IBM's kernel is detachable and can be used to build or wrap a
: >myriad of different operating systems around it, ranging from PDAs to
: >high end database servers.

: I don't understand the relationship here.  It's probably true that IBM
: isn't copying NT's kernel.  However, that has nothing to with
: detachability and running different OSes.  Say you have an interactive TV
: system.  You could run a stripped-down NT kernel on the set-top boxes and
: a similar (different drivers and management software, etc) on the media
: servers at the head-end.  Of course if you just want to run different OSes,
: you can already run OS/2 apps on a stock NT.

But the problem is, you don't have a stripped down NT.  Even Win95 does
not use NT's kernel.

A stripped down version of an OS is still that OS.  Detachability means
the kernel can be used on an entirely different OS.   If I have Workplace
on a Taiwanese made PDA, it's not a stripped down version of OS/2.



: >The same cannot be said of NT's kernel.  NT's kernel seems to have
: >functionality specific to NT and Win32, which is why it's a hybrid, since

: It's a hybrid between a microkernel and a modular layered design.  The
B: modules that implement specific functionality can be removed, added, or
: interchanged.

Monolithic and microkernel OSes can both be modular, layered designs.
The current OS/2 is a monolithic OS, but by design it's also modular.



: >Having said that, a hybrid is not a bad idea since consolidating OS
: >functions into a partly monolithic design helps "compact" the OS for
: >reduced size and improved speed.  And Microsoft can afford to do this
: >because it has only one NT.

: That's true, but there's nothing monolithic about the design.


But I strongly suspect that every new version of NT since v3.1 is
increasingly monolithic.  It's the one way they can optimize for speed
and reduce memory---consolidate and integrate functions more into the
kernel and into larger and fewer modules.

In fact we can go back to the thing we have about Direct Draw or ring 0
graphics APIs.  Introducing them into a future version of NT practically
makes NT a monolithic OS, because you have Windows/games/PC specific
functions dumped into the kernel or kernel space.  Just a hypothetical
and rhetorical example.

Rgds,

Chris


