: Yes, but you need to study what a micro-kernel is supposed to deliver.  Your
: thought process here really doesn't make much sense.  The idea is that if
: you have a micro-kernel, you can build ANY personality on top of that layer.
: With NT's model, you build on top of NT's subsystem, which in turn is built
: on top of NT's kernel.  Granted, Microsoft has some interesting idea's to
: get around some of these issues, but in short, they tend to be "kludgey"
: and strange looking when you investigate the actual implementation.  So,
: you're really stuck (for the most part) with whatever Microsoft delivers
: with their OS.  The same _should_ not be "as" true for a micro-kernel design.

:  >
:  >>The same cannot be said of NT's kernel.  NT's kernel seems to have
:  >>functionality specific to NT and Win32, which is why it's a hybrid, since
:  >
:  >It's a hybrid between a microkernel and a modular layered design.  The

: Sounds like you are saying, "monolithic".  This is what is considered the
: traditional Unix kernel design.  Good, then we agree on what I've said! :)

:  >modules that implement specific functionality can be removed, added, or
:  >interchanged.
:  >

: This is true of any modular based system.  This is the whole point of
: making something modular.  Again, this is no different from what I've
: been saying.


:  >>Having said that, a hybrid is not a bad idea since consolidating OS
:  >>functions into a partly monolithic design helps "compact" the OS for
:  >>reduced size and improved speed.  And Microsoft can afford to do this
:  >>because it has only one NT.
:  >
:  >That's true, but there's nothing monolithic about the design.

: Unless I've been misinformed, monolithic does not mean singular module
: design.  It means that EVERYTHING (all OS functionality) is bundled into
: a single kernel.  With a micro-kernel, only the most basic and paramount of
: features are placed in the kernel.


:  Later,
:    Greg Copeland
:    gcope@airmail.net


: P.S.  I welcome any feedback on my statements or interpretations and
: understandings of kernel design.  Since this in NOT my area of expertise,
: I must admit I'm walking toward a grey area here.  Keep in mind, I do
: feel comfortable with what I've stated.  In short (ya I know....too late),
: this leaves the door open for error.


You're pretty much on the right trail, Greg, except that on a monolithic
OS, it is not necessary that *everything* and *all* OS functionality
should be in the kernel to be judged a monolithic.

The criteria and ideal in my belief that what a true microkernel should
be, is that it must be OS-independent.  It must have functions that is
-universally- basic to all OSes, but not stuff that is specific, bias or
eschewed to one OS over the other.  There should not be something that is
"Mac-ness", "Window-ness", "OS/2-ness", or even "Unix-ness".
The kernel must indeed be fully "open".

